'''Pape Matar Sarr''' ({{IPA|fr|pap matɑʁ sɑʁ}}; born 14 September 2002) is a Senegalese professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for {{English football updater|TottenhH}} club [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] and the [[Senegal national football team|Senegal national team]].

== Club career ==

===Metz===
Pape Matar Sarr made his professional debut with [[Génération Foot]] in his native country of [[Senegal]], before signing a five-year contract with [[Ligue 1]] side [[FC Metz|Metz]] on 15 September 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|date=15 September 2020|title=Official {{!}} Metz sign Pape Matar Sarr from Génération Foot {{!}} Get French Football News|url=https://www.getfootballnewsfrance.com/2020/official-metz-signe-pape-matar-sarr-from-generation-foot/|access-date=8 June 2021|website=www.getfootballnewsfrance.com}}</ref>

Sarr was initially sent to play for Metz's second team in [[Championnat National 1|Championnat National 2]], but made only one appearance before he was recalled to the first team squad following the season being halted due to the [[COVID-19 pandemic in France]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Bouchacourt|first=Jérome|date=23 April 2021|title=La FFF a décidé d'arrêter les championnats de National 2 et D2 Féminine|url=https://www.footamateur.fr/la-fff-a-decide-darreter-les-championnats-de-national-2-et-d2-feminine/|access-date=8 June 2021|website=Foot Amateur|language=fr-FR}}</ref> He made his debut for the Metz first team on 29 November 2020 in a Ligue 1 game against [[Stade Brestois 29|Brest]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Secret|first=Bryan|date=29 November 2020|title=Résultat et résumé Metz – Brest, Ligue 1 Uber Eats, 12e journée|url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/match-direct/ligue-1/2020-2021/metz-brest-live/477270|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 January 2021|website=[[L'Équipe]]|language=fr}}</ref> On 31 January 2021, Sarr scored his first goal in Ligue 1 in the reverse fixture, a 4–2 away victory over Brest.<ref>{{Cite web|date=31 January 2021|title=BREST 2–4 METZ|url=https://www.ligue1.com/match|access-date=8 June 2021|website=Ligue1|language=en}}</ref>

===Tottenham Hotspur===
On 27 August 2021, Sarr signed for [[Premier League]] club [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]. He was loaned back to Metz until the end of the [[2021–22 FC Metz season|2021–22 season]].<ref>{{Cite web|date=27 August 2021|title=Pape Matar Sarr signs from Metz|url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/2021/august/pape-matar-sarr-signs-from-metz/|access-date=27 August 2021|website=|publisher=[[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.]]}}</ref> On 1 January 2023, Sarr finally made his long-awaited Premier League debut coming on as an 80th-minute substitute for [[Yves Bissouma]] in a 2–0 home loss to [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Sang|first=Kiplagat|date=1 January 2023|title=Pape Matar Sarr: Senegal wonderkid makes Tottenham Hotspur debut after 18 months|url=https://www.goal.com/en-gb/amp/news/pape-matar-sarr-senegal-wonderkid-makes-tottenham-hotspur-debut-after-18-months/bltf7640624f893bda7|access-date=4 January 2023|website=Goal (website)}}</ref> Since his first appearance against Aston Villa, Sarr has featured regularly for Spurs, either coming off the bench or starting. He got his first goal contribution, an assist on 28 May 2023, in the last game of the season, a 4–1 away win at [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]]. On 19 August 2023, Sarr scored his first goal for Tottenham Hotspur on their first home game of the [[2023–24 Premier League]] season, a 2–0 win against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://talksport.com/football/1539140/pape-matar-sarr-marcus-rashford-celebration-tottenham-manchester-united/ |title=Tottenham fans love what Pape Matar Sarr did after scoring in win over Manchester United |publisher=talkSPORT |date=19 August 2023 }}</ref>

On 2 January 2024, after a run of impressive performances, Sarr extended his contract with Tottenham until 2030.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2 January 2024 |title=New deal for Pape |url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/2024/january/new-deal-for-pape/ |access-date=2 January 2024 |website= |publisher=Tottenham Hotspur F.C. |language=en}}</ref>

Sarr provided the cross prior to [[Brennan Johnson]]'s opening goal in the [[2025 Europa League Final]], which Tottenham would go on to win 1–0, earning Sarr the first major club honour of his career.

== International career ==
Sarr made his debut for [[Senegal national football team|Senegal national team]] on 26 March 2021 in an [[2021 Africa Cup of Nations qualification Group I|AFCON 2021 qualifier]] against [[Congo national football team|Congo]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[ESPN]]|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match?gameId=596273|title=Congo v Senegal game report|date=26 March 2021}}</ref> On 6 February 2022, he won the [[2021 Africa Cup of Nations]] with Senegal.<ref name=":0" /> He made one appearance at the tournament, appearing as a substitute in the 3–1 semi-final win over [[Burkina Faso national football team|Burkina Faso]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/2022/february/internationals-pape-helps-senegal-reach-afcon-final/|title=Internationals – Pape helps Senegal reach AFCON final|date=2 February 2022|access-date=19 November 2023|publisher=Tottenham Hotspur F.C.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/2022/february/afcon-glory-for-pape/|title=AFCON glory for Pape|date=6 February 2022|access-date=19 November 2023|publisher=Tottenham Hotspur F.C.}}</ref>

He was appointed a [[National Order of the Lion|Grand Officer of the National Order of the Lion]] by [[President of Senegal]], [[Macky Sall]] following the nation's victory at the 2021 Africa Cup of Nations.<ref name= "reuters">{{cite web |title=Cash prizes, real estate, and highest honours as Senegal celebrates Nations Cup heroes |url=https://www.reuters.com/lifestyle/sports/cash-prizes-real-estate-highest-honours-senegal-celebrates-nations-cup-heroes-2022-02-08/ |website=[[Reuters]] |access-date=28 March 2023 |date=8 February 2022}}</ref> On 21 July, he was named [[Confederation of African Football|CAF]]'s Male Young Player of the Year at the 2022 [[CAF Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/2022/july/sarr-named-caf-young-player-of-the-year/|title=Sarr named CAF Young Player of the Year|date=21 July 2022|access-date=19 November 2023|publisher=Tottenham Hotspur F.C.}}</ref>

Sarr was included in Senegal's squad for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]], where he appeared as a substitute in the team's 3–1 group stage win over [[Qatar national football team|Qatar]]<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2022/nov/25/qatar-v-senegal-world-cup-2022-live-score-updates|title= Qatar 1–3 Senegal: World Cup 2022 – as it happened|date=26 November 2022|access-date=19 November 2023|website=The Guardian}}</ref> and 3–0 round of 16 loss to [[England national football team|England]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2022/dec/04/england-v-senegal-world-cup-2022-last-16-live|title=England 3–0 Senegal: World Cup 2022, last 16 – as it happened|date=5 December 2022|access-date=19 November 2023|website=The Guardian}}</ref>

On 18 November 2023, he scored his first senior international goal in a 4–0 win over [[South Sudan national football team|South Sudan]] in a [[2026 FIFA World Cup]] [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification (CAF)|qualifier]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/2023/november/sarr-scores-first-ever-goal-for-senegal-in-double-quick-time|title= Sarr scores first-ever goal for Senegal... in double-quick time!|date=18 November 2023|publisher=Tottenham Hotspur F.C.}}</ref>

In December 2023, Sarr was named in Senegal's squad for the postponed [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations]] held in the [[Ivory Coast]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/africa/67840713|title=Afcon 2023: Senegal and Sadio Mane set for defence of title|date=29 December 2023|access-date=29 December 2023|work=BBC Sport Africa}}</ref>

